data.title: I could have been as big as the Beatles: Ben Kingsley reveals things might have turned out very differently, if only he’d listened to John Lennon...
data.meta_description: He won an Oscar for Gandhi and he’s got a knighthood to boot. But things might have turned out very differently, Ben Kingsley reveals all.
data.text:
He won an Oscar for Gandhi and he’s got a knighthood to boot. But things might have turned out very differently, Ben Kingsley reveals all

When Ben Kingsley was a little boy, he convinced himself he was being followed around by an invisible film crew. He would dream up heroic scenarios in his head and act them out until the invisible director shouted ‘Cut!’ Then he’d retire to his invisible dressing room and rehearse the next invisible take.

‘That’s the sort of chap I was,’ says Kingsley now. ‘Isolated in my own thoughts, living my fantasies, and absolutely determined to make my parents and siblings take notice of me.’

His doctor father – inspired by the 1947 film The Secret Life Of Walter Mitty – nicknamed him after its star. ‘You are the Danny Kaye of our family,’ he would tell his son. Kingsley – now Sir Ben, with a distinguished acting career that includes an Oscar, two Baftas and two Golden Globes – says that with having to fulfil the demands of the invisible film crew and the expectations of his family, life was exhausting.

After Gandhi: Sir Ben and wife Daniela at the Taj Mahal in 2009

‘We do tend to become our nickname, I’m afraid, and as the showman of the family, I tried to make them laugh. They were not the jolliest bunch, so it wasn’t easy.’ He has described his parents as being cold and remote, but he says now that this drove him on. ‘I was noisy, with an outgoing personality that they tried to control – one of the recurring sounds of my childhood was the word “Sssh!” But if you try to keep talent suppressed, it will struggle all the more to get out and be heard.’

He was reminded of his boyhood ambitions during the making of his latest film, Hugo, in which 14-year-old Londoner Asa Butterfield plays an orphan who lives behind the clock in a train station in 1930s Paris. Kingsley, 67, is a grumpy toyshop owner desperate to conceal his past as a famed maker of silent movies. The family film is visually stunning, brilliantly directed by Martin Scorsese, and well acted with an ensemble cast including Sacha Baron Cohen, Jude Law, Richard Griffiths, Ray Winstone and Christopher Lee. But the lion’s share of it, from the pathos to the laughter, rests on Asa’s young shoulders.

‘Yes, I can clearly remember how determined I was at his age, so there was no distance between me and Asa,’ says Kingsley. ‘The relationship we had was very close and direct. There was no clutter, just chemistry, because I still have a childlike elasticity inside me. I wasn’t fortunate enough to be acting professionally like Asa when I was his age. But I’d known since I was about eight years old that that was what I wanted to do.’

Flashback: Ben in his latest film Hugo with co-star Asa Butterfield

A touching tale unfolds. His father had taken young Ben – born Krishna Bhanji – to the cinema near their home in Salford, Lancashire, to see a film called Never Take No For An Answer, about an Italian orphan, Peppino, who has a donkey called Violetta. The donkey falls sick, and Peppino petitions the Pope to allow the animal into church so it can be healed at the altar. ‘I was very influenced by that picture. It opened a door for me,’ says Kingsley. But it turns out there is even more to the story than that.

Afterwards, in the cinema foyer, the manager spots Krishna, mistakes him for the actor who played Peppino, Vittorio Manunta, and holds him shoulder high, shouting, ‘Look, the star of our film is here,’ Kingsley recalls, ‘I loved all that attention. And yes, I suppose I did look like him.’ His new ambition stood him in good stead at Manchester Grammar School. ‘I was in a school play, Our Town, but when I told one of my classmates, Johnny Hill, that I wanted to be an actor, he said, “What a waste of a good education.” That confused me because on the one hand I was being called the Danny Kaye of the family and on the other I was being told, “Oh, you shouldn’t be doing that.”’

When I told one of my classmates, Johnny Hill, that I wanted to be an actor, he said, 'What a waste of a good education'

Soon after leaving school, and taking any acting job he could find, he teetered on the brink of an alternative career. John Lennon and Ringo Starr saw him in a play called A Smashing Day, staged by their late manager, Brian Epstein. Kingsley played a busker and wrote and sang all his own songs for the show.

‘They came backstage afterwards and told me I ought to become a rock star. I was only about 21, and before I knew it, I was being ushered in to meet their music publisher, Dick James, and across a vast mahogany desk he told me he could mould me into a singer as big as the Beatles. It was very tempting, but I was terrified, and I said I’d think about it. That same day I was offered a season acting at Chichester Festival theatre, so I accepted and after that I never looked back. ‘I wouldn’t have lasted as a rock star in the musical sense. I’d have fallen among thieves, partying every night in my hotel room and enjoying a rock’n’roll life. I would have had none of the discipline I need as an actor – that’s been a life saver.’

His biggest break came with Gandhi in 1982. Only now does he admit how daunted he was. ‘I’d been taking baby steps in acting, but suddenly Sir Richard Attenborough wanted me for this very ambitious film he was directing. I auditioned, and I was blessed because before I’d even finished he told me I’d got the part. When the realisation sank in, and when shooting was about to begin, I was so overcome with nerves that I actually cried. I didn’t know how I was going to get through it, but I had to, so I did. It was like facing a sheer mountain face every day, knowing I would have to somehow climb it – and then start all over again tomorrow.’

The Oscar Kingsley got for Gandhi established him as a thespian warhorse

The Oscar he got for that established him as a thespian warhorse, and the inevitable knighthood followed. When he was billed as Sir Ben Kingsley on film and show posters – against all theatrical tradition – and it was said he insisted on even his co-stars addressing him by his title, other luvvie grandees were outraged. Sir Anthony Hopkins described his stance as ‘insanity’. Lord Puttnam called him ‘barmy’. Sir Roger Moore said he was guilty of ‘pretentious b******s’.

Kingsley insists it was all a mistake and explains that his title was added to the posters by an over-enthusiastic lackey, against his wishes. How ever, tellingly, he explained that being bullied as a child, and suffering a ‘steady stream’ of racism, had made him particularly proud of his knighthood. ‘I think it’s a reflection of how an uncomfortable childhood can lead to high achievement,’ he says.

But if Kingsley has found it hard to shake off the charge of pompousness, it is perhaps partly due to his aura of intensity and gravitas. In fact, he is charming and informal company, interested in everything and everyone, and ready to poke fun at himself. When he made a guest appearance as himself in The Sopranos, the starstruck gangsters sent him up mercilessly in the show as ‘Sir Kingsley’. Today, he tells me, ‘I enjoyed every self-satirising line. It was a conscious cartoon – it was me, but it wasn’t really me. I even added a few touches to that script myself.’

Kingsley’s friends say he has mellowed since 2007, when he married his fourth wife, Brazilian actress Daniela Barbosa de Carneiro, who uses the stage name Daniela Lavender. At 37, she is three decades younger than him, and several inches taller in her heels. ‘We aren’t aware of the age gap,’ she says. ‘The sexual chemistry is very active.’ Kingsley himself is more restrained. ‘She’s very intuitive, and extraordinarily bright,’ he says of her. ‘We are very happy.’

Not surprisingly, he can’t wait to get home. ‘I’m able now to enjoy the domestic, nourishing sides of life. When I’m away, I miss cooking in my kitchen, spending time with my wife. Our home is a very strong focus. I get very homesick, but I know it’s there waiting for me when I come back.’ His new film was mostly shot in the Home Counties, so he made the 90-minute commute from his £2.5m country house near Chipping Norton in Oxfordshire to the set every day. ‘I’d be up at 4.30am, out by 5.30am, in make-up at 7am, and ready by 9am. A full day, then the 90-minute drive home to Daniela and all the familiar smells and surroundings. Then I’d fall into my own bed. Sheer luxury. Lucky me.’
